  "summary": "Keyword co-occurrence in bundled CLI/server output requires human review",
  "details": "autotel-devtools@1.0.4 ships minified/bundled CLI and server JavaScript under dist/ (cli.js, cli.cjs, index.js, index.cjs, server/index.js, server/index.cjs, widget.global.js). Pattern matches fired on keyword co-occurrence within these single-line bundles: Buffer.from(..., 'base64') decoding alongside.toString() calls, and the tokens 'ping' and 'POST' appearing in the same files. These primitives are common to legitimate developer-tool bundles (HTTP clients, base64 helpers for assets/icons, health-check endpoints, telemetry pings) as well as to exfiltration code. No corroborating behavioral trace ties these primitives to an attacker-controlled destination, credential read, lifecycle hook, or import-time side effect in the available evidence. package.json lifecycle hooks, top-level module side effects, and the destination of any POST were not confirmed. Routing to human review so a reviewer can de-minify the dist/ bundles and confirm whether the base64 decode + POST shape is benign tooling or a hardcoded callback.",
